  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - ENCHANTER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>DARK ELF ENCHANTRESS, LEVEL 1-7 OR SO</font> - <small>Xxtayce E`Tiernal, Fennin Ro</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><p>As much fun as it is to be an evil dark elf, I would seriously
recommend NOT following Innoruuk. I promise, it will mess up
everything you were hoping to do as an enchanter. I tell you this
now because I would like to warn you with enough time for you to
recreate your character. By level 7, even, you have probably not
had the chance to leave Nektulous Forest, and if you have, it
probably hasn't been for very long. If you are not Agnostic, you
will do yourself a great favor by starting over, and with a good
knowledge of how to play your character, it shouldn't take you
too long to get to level seven.<br>
<br>
I am here to help you with your quest for knowledge of the
mysterious arts of enchantment, and to shed a little light upon
the somewhat difficult path ahead of you. So, Vendui brothers and
sisters, good luck and Innoruuk kyorl dos.<br>
<br>
Level One<br>
You are born a naked dark elf within the city of Neriak, given
nothing but the book of discord, some food, and the little dagger
that you begin with.<br>
<br>
Unless you plan on not being able to be buffed, healed, or helped
in any way by other player characters, destroy the book of
discord, and make your way to the 'Tower of the Spurned' as your
tattered note suggests. If you know not your way around Neriak,
now is a good time to find out, or to ask other Tier'Dal nearby
for assistance. Just know that if you are in Neriak Commons, you
are in the right zone, so look around. Others know it simply as
the casters' guild, and if you are looking for it on your own,
and you happen across a place called 'Neriak Down Under' (which
has the bank inside it, by the by) you know you are close. <br>
<br>
Whether you do this before going to see your guild master or
after, be sure to scribe and mem the two spells you begin with,
practice them until your skill is up to 5 or so, and use them
wherever needed.<br>
<br>
Carnia V'Retta is on the bottom floor of the caster's guild in
the very last room at the end of the hallway. Give her your note,
place upon yourself the robe of a caster, put your practice
points into piercing, at the moment, and head out to Nektulous
Forest. <br>
<br>
There is a place within Nek Forest referred to as the 'Newbie
log' which is where nearly every new child begins their journey,
and where the occasional more seasoned member will sit to guard
and protect if necessary. LOC pos 1137, neg 206. If you leave
Neriak, there is a mountain in front of you, just go around it to
the left side, and you should soon see the log, in front of a
road, with people already beginning their attempt to level.<br>
<br>
I know that at level one, those white spiderlings look very
tempting, but beware: they are quite the socail creature and will
come from miles around to help one of their kind if you are
fighting them. So, for level one, I would kill the black wolves
(who will attack you no matter what) and most importantly moss
snakes. Moss snakes are perfect for a low level, and the loot
that they drop is most often stackable so you can carry more of
it, and they should easily get you to level 2. Just remember to
stick close to the newbie log, do not cross the road until much
later in level, and if you are in over your head, use /y and
don't run around, and people should help you. If you do happen to
die, you don't lose experience, you get the free food and water
still, and you get a chance to learn your way around. (Just
remember to loot your corpse early.) <br>
<br>
One more thing I forgot: decaying skeletons. These can be quite
profitable as well, considering that they drop some coin (useful
for buying spells), their bone chips are stackable, and if you
happen to come across a necro who is willing to buy a stack of
bonechips, it can be quite profitable. (A stack of bone chips
goes for about 5plat on Fennin Ro, so do the math.) The only
difficulty with these are the ones who have weapons because they
hit harder, but if you see one with a staff of any kind - go for
it! Chanters will probably use staffs most of their lives, as
will most casters, and if you work up your 1hb or 2hb early you
will thank yourself for it.<br>
<br>
Level 2 - 3<br>
<br>
It is time to go back to town to sell the loot you have
collected, practice some more in piercing if you have not yet
found a staff, or practice a bit in 1 hand blunt if it is a
cracked staff or 2 hand blunt if it is a worn great staff. If you
have the money, now is a good time to buy a spell or two as well.
(The one who sells level one and level 4 spells is in the
downstairs room of the caster's guild to the right of the door as
soon as you enter the room with the merchants who sell chanter
spells.<br>
<br>
I know that if you have the money for the spells now, you
probably only have money for one (unless some kind person took
pity on you and gave you a few gold, or if you managed to collect
a stack of bone chips to sell to a needy necro), so I will tell
you the spells in order of their importance to your survival. <br>
<br>
Depending on whether you have enough money to buy tiny daggers
(another merchant, same room, somewhere around 1silver, 1copper
per dagger and absolutely necessary to create your pet), I would
suggest either Pendril's Animation or Shallow Breath. The
animations will be all of your pet spells for the rest of your
life, so get used to those. (Not all of them can be found in
Neriak, but that comes at level 8, and is not absolutely
necesssary to know yet, just fyi.) To warn you, enchanter pets
have the weakest pets in the game, so be prepared for that one,
and be prepared to share the tanking abilities between you and
your pet often. If it is necessary to save your life, and if you
haven't pissed the enemy off that your pet can't distract the
enemy, leave your pet and run for the guards. They are good extra
damage, terrible tanks, but will help you more often than you can
imagine. Just know that you cannot control your pets like other
pet classes can, and that your pet will only deal out damage if
you have been hit or swung at by an enemy. <br>
<br>
Shallow Breath is a DOT (damage over time), and is helpful within
a fight for pulling or to deal out a little more damage when
necessary, but basically you will have the same strategy as in
level one, only with another enemy to add to the fun: Fire
Beetles.<br>
<br>
Fire Beetles are social just as with spiderlings, but for some
reason, they do not seem to gang up on you as much as those pesky
spiders do, and most importantly, they don't poison you! So even
if the fight is close, you won't die of poison even if you win...
The thing to remember with fire beetles is to look around you
before doing any fighting, make sure no more are nearby, and try
to kill it quickly. Fire beetle eyes do not stack, but they are
an added light source, and you can keep one in your secondary
slot on your body to provide light or to keep them in another
place other than your inventory slots so that you can carry more.
They obviously sell better than the stackable items, so you may
want to collect those instead, but it is entirely up to your
discretion. And, as tempting as the spiderlings look, hold off on
them until level 4 or so... Keep up the same strategy with level
2 as with level one, only this time with a spell or two, and if
you have to run back to the guards for any reason, go into town
to sell so that you can have more money on you, and buy more
spells when possible. When you level, if you have not yet found a
staff, keep up with your piercing, but place perhaps a point or
two into one handed blunt every now and again if possible, so
that you can have a little bit of practice in the weapon skill
for when you find yourself a staff. (Most staffs that you will
see auctioned in east commons will be one handed blunt, including
your epic quest item, so unless you happen to find a worn great
staff, cracked staffs will be better for your cause.)<br>
<br>
Level 4<br>
<br>
The only difference here is that you get new spells (if you can
afford them) and you can now fight the occasional lone spiderling
(if you can find them). If you can afford a backpack around this
time as well, it will help you out a lot to get one. (somewhere
around 2 gold, I believe, but I could be wrong)<br>
<br>
Your level 4 spells of most importance are Fear (if you plan to
make your enemy run away with your pet beating the crap out of it
while you cast on it every now and again and wait for fear to
wear off so you can recast - useful in later levels, but you can
make do without it otherwise), enfeeblement (weakens your enemy),
Invisibility (good for going through dangerous places if you have
somewhere to go and do not wish to encounter living enemies on
the way), haze (your next line of sheilding spells), Juli's
Animation (self-explanatory), Suffocating Sphere (the upgraded
version of Shallow Breath), Mesmerise (absolutely necessary for
crowd control at later levels, ok for it now but there is not
really anywhere to use it until level 8 - just get it and
practice it on yourself, your pet, or a corpse while away from
guards), and Tashan (lowers magic resistance, and a spell you
will be using until almost level 20 or so when you get the
upgraded version of it). The illusion spells are sold on the top
floor of the caster's building, and are quite helpful if you need
to do a quest or go through an area that is unfriendly to dark
elves, but not yet absolutely necessary since the guards will
kill you if they see you with a human illusion on.<br>
<br>
The other change with level 4 is that you can begin to take
skeletons that are white to you - but be careful, they hit hard
and are extremely social... And you can also take the shadow
wolves and black bears, who will attack you no matter what
anyway, so you might as well.<br>
<br>
Level 5-7 <br>
<br>
Here is where you get the remainder of your level one and four
spells if you have not already (caster's realm spell list is a
great way to learn what they all do in detail), and to get a
group at the skeleton pyramid/wizard spire (LOC pos 657, neg 704)
or at the monolith (nearby the zone to East Commonlands LOC neg
2678 neg 545, follow the road to the left of the newbie log, over
the bridge, and straight out to the zone, the monolith will be on
your left facing the zone) and attempt to stay here until level 8
so you can get your new spells before venturing out to East
Commonlands to attempt to join an orc group. <br>
<br>
Innoruuk kyorl dos, may Innoruuk (the father of the Tier'Dal)
bless you, and good luck in your questing of enchantments. <br>
<br>
Xxtayce E`Tiernal<br>
Enchantress of the 32nd season<br>
House Undraeth<br>
Fennin Ro<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
